Headline::::
Tesco slows sales decline as recovery gathers pace




DateTime::::2016-03-08T13:17:11+0000



<p><a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/tesco">Tesco</a> has halved the pace of its sales decline in the past month as price cuts have helped stem the loss of customers elsewhere.</p>

<p>The UK’s biggest supermarket enjoyed its best performance since July, with sales down 0.8% in the 12 weeks to 28 February, compared with <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" draggable="true" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/09/uk-grocery-market-gets-a-boost-from-detox-january">a 1.6% decline revealed a month</a> earlier, according to analysts Kantar Worldpanel. </p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/26/tesco-considering-cutting-store-staff-by-39000-over-three-years">Tesco considering cutting store staff by 39,000 over three years</a> </p>

<p>Separate figures from analysis firm Nielsen suggested Tesco was doing even better, with sales falling by just 0.5%, the chain’s best performance since November 2013.</p>

<p>Mike Watkins, Nielsen’s UK head of retail and business insight, said: “Tesco has been improving the basics, including its pricing. This has encouraged more visits and attracted back shoppers who had previously defected. <br/>“Their new customer proposition highlights the benefits of having a large variety of store types – physical and online. <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/supermarkets">Supermarkets</a> offering more locations, good private label and a superior customer experience – not just lower prices – tend to be more successful, and these are some of the areas where Tesco are focusing.”</p>

<p>The strong sales performance is good news for Dave Lewis, Tesco’s chief executive, who is under pressure to show results from his turnaround plan, which kicked off in autumn 2014.</p>

<p>The improvement in sales came alongside a general pickup in the grocery market in February. Sales for the sector rose 0.5%, the fastest pace of growth since October, as chocolate sales rose 13% in February – thanks to Valentine’s Day and early preparations for Easter. Sparkling wine sales also continued to soar – up 15% last month.</p>

<p>Tesco’s trade increase came at the expense of Asda and <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/morrisons">Morrisons</a>, where the pace of sales declines increased. Asda’s sales fell by 4% in the three months to the end of February, the chain’s worst performance recorded by Kantar.</p>

<p>The struggling retailer has lost 0.8 percentage points of market share over the past year. It controls 16.2% of UK grocery sales, putting it behind Sainsbury’s, which is now the UK’s second biggest supermarket with 16.8% market share. Tesco’s market share is 28.4%.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/29/amazon-enters-fresh-food-market-with-morrisons-deal">Amazon enters fresh food market with Morrisons deal</a> </p>

<p>Asda boss Andy Clarke has said <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/dec/18/andy-clarke-asda-determined-not-shelve-five-year-plan">he is sticking to a plan of protecting profits and cutting prices</a>, despite 15 months of falling sales culminating in the company’s <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/feb/18/asda-quarterly-loss-christmas">worst quarterly trading period</a>. But he is under increasing pressure to turnaround performance before the arrival this autumn of <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/13/asda-poaches-top-sainsburys-director">his potential successor, Roger Burnley</a>, a former Sainsbury’s director.</p>

<p>Sainsbury’s was the only one of the big four chains to see growth over the three-month period. Its sales rose by 0.5%, its eighth consecutive period of growth.</p>

<p>Morrisons’ sales declined by 3.2%, compared with a 2.2% fall revealed by Kantar last month. The Bradford-based chain’s sales continue to be impacted by store closures and price cuts.</p>

<p>The changing face of the grocery market is clearly marked in the latest figures as the German discounters Aldi and <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/business/lidl">Lidl</a> continue to grow rapidly. Lidl’s sales rose 18.9%; Aldi’s sales rose 15.1%, taking their combined market share to 10%.</p>

<p>The Co-operative Group also continued its strong period of growth, with sales up 1.9%, as it benefits from the trend towards shopping little and often, as well as improvements to its stores, pricing and product range.</p>




