I dunno.I'm not a regular Lidl shopper - but I can see the appeal. Definitely cheaper and produce is actually pretty good quality. It's that last bit I love - fruit, veg and meat better than my local Sainsburys/Coop and noticeably cheaper.Whilst they look "no-frills" - staff actually seem competent and they manage to keep shelves stocked.I think where the big supermarkets went wrong was their continuous reduction in the quality of their 'premium ranges' - Waitrose and M&S aside, they're pretty much universally mediocre now. To take an example, there's half an aisle of bacon - all the cuts/brands/cures you could want - but every f'in one of them (Denhay aside) seems to produce that nitrate-water scum when you cook it. My shopping now is almost going back to the 'high-street-of-yore" model - half a dozen shops required each week to actually fill a kitchen with decent value (in a non-derogatory sense) food.



